            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.XVII.R21</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>&ldquo;O my little Dorrit!&rdquo;</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-c86e076a-7fff-244e-c869-407f875c0278\"><br />This phrase, uttered in despair by a weeping Clennam, is the last of the chapter (LD 699) and of this Note. Ending in this manner, with Clennam dwelling on Little Dorrit&rsquo;s &ldquo;absence in his altered fortunes&rdquo; and his &ldquo;need of such a face of love and truth&rdquo; (699), allows Dickens to strengthen rather than &ldquo;weaken her next appearance,&rdquo; as he indicates on the left when he chooses not to include a letter from her in this number (LD.XVII.L7). Readers will have to wait until the final chapter of the next number for Clennam&rsquo;s plea to be answered. </span></p>"
        }
